This paper discusses the validity of the Scopus SNIP indicator, which is a bibliometric indicator used in the field of computer science to measure the impact of scientific journals. The paper specifically addresses issues related to field classifications and the lack of statistical analysis in some indicators, which are relevant to several sub-categories of computer science. cs.DL (Digital Libraries) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval) are likely sub-categories because they are concerned with bibliometrics and information retrieval. cs.CY (Computational Geometry) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) are also possible sub-categories because they involve the analysis of complex data structures and networks, which are relevant to bibliometric analysis. Finally, cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) is a possible sub-category because it deals with the validation of data and the detection of errors, which are relevant to the issues raised in the paper.
